âš¡ Script

#!/bin/bash
â†’ #! tells Linux this is a script
â†’ /bin/bash means use the bash shell to run it

[ARCH]
arch=$(uname -a)
â†’ arch is variable name
â†’ $(..) means run a command & save result
â†’ uname is system info
â†’ -a means all info (OS/kernel/architecture)

[CPU PHYSICAL]
cpuf=$(grep "physical id" /proc/cpuinfo | wc -l)
â†’ /proc/cpuinfo is a CPU info file
â†’ grep "physical id" searches for CPU ID (each physical has 1)
â†’ wc -l is word count + count lines
â†’ counts the number of physical CPU sockets (usually 1)

[CPU VIRTUAL]
cpuv=$(grep "processor" /proc/cpuinfo | wc -l)
â†’ each processor line = 1 logical core/thread
â†’ counts total vCPUs

[RAM]
ram_total=$(free --mega | awk '$1 == "Mem:" {print $2}')
â†’ free --mega shows ram in MB
â†’ awk is a text picker
â†’ $1 == "Mem" choose memory line
â†’ {print $2} means print total RAM
â†’ $ means each column

ram_use=$(free --mega | awk '$1 == "Mem:" {print $3}')
â†’ $3 means print used RAM

ram_percent=$(free --mega | awk '$1 == "Mem:" {printf("%.2f"), $3/$2*100}')
â†’ $3/$2*100 means used divide by total x100
â†’ printf("%.2f") shows 2 decimal

[DISK]
disk_total=$(df -m | grep "/dev/" | grep -v "/boot" | awk '{disk_t += $2} END {printf ("%.1fGb\n"), disk_t/1024}')
â†’ df -m means disk usage in MB
â†’ /dev/ means real disk partitions
â†’ -v "/boot" means exclude boot partition
â†’ $2 means total space
â†’ adds all partitions together and converts MB to GB excluding boot

disk_use=$(df -m | grep "/dev/" | grep -v "/boot" | awk '{disk_u += $3} END {print disk_u}')
â†’ $3 means used disk space
â†’ adds used space from all disk

disk_percent=$(df -m | grep "/dev/" | grep -v "/boot" | awk '{disk_u += $3} {disk_t+= $2} END {printf("%d"), disk_u/disk_t*100}')
â†’ adds used and total disk
â†’ computers (used/total) * 100 and prints as integer

[CPU LOAD]
cpul=$(vmstat 1 2 | tail -1 | awk '{printf $15}')
â†’ vmstat 1 2 means system stats, 2nd sample is accurate
â†’ $15 means CPU idle percentage
â†’ saved as cpul

cpu_op=$(expr 100 - $cpul)
â†’ subtracts idle % from 100
â†’ gives CPU usage %

cpu_fin=$(printf "%.1f" $cpu_op)
â†’ formats CPU usage to 1 decimal place

[LAST BOOT]
lb=$(who -b | awk '$1 == "system" {print $3 " " $4}')
â†’ who -b means last system boot
â†’ extracts date and time

[LVM USE]
lvmu=$(if [ $(lsblk | grep "lvm" | wc -l) -gt 0 ]; then echo yes; else echo no; fi)
â†’ lsblk means block devices
â†’ checks for logical volume management if it used, outputs yes/no
â†’ storage management system in Linux that lets you flexibly manage disk space
â†’ instead of working directly with fixed-size disk partitions, LVM lets you resize, combine, and move storage dynamically

[TCP CONNECTIONS]
tcpc=$(ss -ta | grep ESTAB | wc -l)
â†’ ss -ta means TCP (transmission control protocol) sockets
â†’ ESTAB means established connections
â†’ counts active TCP connections

[USER LOG]
ulog=$(users | wc -w)
â†’ users means logged in users
â†’ wc -w is count words

[NETWORK]
ip=$(hostname -I)
â†’ prints system IP addresses

mac=$(ip link | grep "link/ether" | awk '{print $2}')
â†’ ip link means network interfaces
â†’ link/ether means MAC address

[SUDO]
cmnd=$(journalctl _COMM=sudo | grep COMMAND | wc -l)
â†’ journalctl means system logs
â†’ _COMM=sudo means sudo logs only
â†’ counts executed sudo commands

âš¡ Script Outputs
Architecture 				     â†’ Type of OS and CPU + kernel
CPU (physical & virtual)       â†’ How many cores the server has
RAM usage 				        â†’ Memory used / total
Disk usage 				        â†’ Storage used / total
CPU load 				        â†’ How busy the server is
Last reboot 				    â†’ When the server was restarted
LVM 					         â†’ Confirms disk security setup (yes/no)
TCP connections 			    â†’ Active network connections
Users 					        â†’ How many users are logged in
IP & MAC 				        â†’ Server network identity
Sudo commands 			        â†’ How many admin commands were run

[GitBook Tests]
0ï¸âƒ£0ï¸âƒ£ apt vs aptitude
-apt installs and removes packages but doesn't resolve complex dependency choices (i.e sudo apt update/sudo apt install sudo/sudo apt remove vim)
-aptitude canhandle dependency conflicts more intelligently by proposing solutions (i.e sudo aptitude install nginx)

0ï¸âƒ£1ï¸âƒ£ What is Born2BeRoot?
â€œBorn2BeRoot is a system administration project where I learned how to install and configure a Linux server in a virtual machine, and how to properly secure it using users, sudo, SSH, firewall, and password policies. The goal is security and best practices.â€

0ï¸âƒ£2ï¸âƒ£ What is a virtual machine (VM)?
â€œA virtual machine is a computer running inside another computer. It allows me to install and configure an operating system in an isolated environment without affecting the host machine.â€

0ï¸âƒ£3ï¸âƒ£ Which OS did you install and why?
â€œI installed Debian because it is a stable and secure Linux distribution, commonly used for servers, and it is beginner-friendly for learning system administration. Debian is more community oriented and widely used, while Rocky targets enterprise (stricter security policies).â€

0ï¸âƒ£4ï¸âƒ£ What is root and why is it important?
â€œRoot is the superuser with full system permissions. The root user is the superuser on a Linux system with full administrative privileges. It can perform any action, including managing users, installing software, and changing system files, which is why it must be used carefully."

0ï¸âƒ£5ï¸âƒ£ Why use sudo instead of logging in as root?
â€œWe use sudo to run commands with temporary root privileges without logging in as root. This keeps the system safer because mistakes or malicious commands canâ€™t directly affect the root account, and all actions are logged for accountability.â€

0ï¸âƒ£6ï¸âƒ£ What is sudoers.d and why not edit /etc/sudoers?
â€œsudoers.d is a directory where we put sudo configuration files. We donâ€™t edit /etc/sudoers directly because a mistake there could break sudo completely. Using sudoers.d keeps the system safe and organized, and allows separate rules without risking the main configuration.â€

0ï¸âƒ£7ï¸âƒ£ Why configure SSH, and what changes did you make?
â€œI configured SSH to allow secure remote access to my virtual machine from the terminal. I also improved security by disabling root login, using a non-default port, and allowing only trusted users to connect. I changed the SSH port to reduce automated attacks on the default SSH port. I disabled root login via SSH to prevent direct root access and improve security."

0ï¸âƒ£8ï¸âƒ£ What is a firewall, and why use UFW (Uncomplicated FireWall) ?
â€œA firewall protects the computer by controlling which network connections are allowed or blocked, defending against unauthorized or malicious access. I used UFW because it is simple to configure and provides an easy way to enforce these rules.â€

0ï¸âƒ£9ï¸âƒ£ What are password policies, and why use PAM?
â€œPassword policies are rules that enforce strong passwords, like minimum length or complexity, to make accounts more secure. I used PAM (Pluggable Authentication Modules) because it manages these rules safely and reliably on Linux systems. PAM (Pluggable Authentication Modules) is a system that manages authentication and password rules..â€

1ï¸âƒ£0ï¸âƒ£ What is the monitoring script, and why did you create it?
â€œThe monitoring script is a small program I created to display system information, such as CPU, RAM, disk usage, uptime, and architecture. I scheduled it with cron so it runs automatically every few minutes, helping monitor the system without manually checking.â€

1ï¸âƒ£1ï¸âƒ£ What is cron, and why use it?
â€œCron is a Linux tool used to schedule tasks to run automatically at specific times or intervals. I used it to run my monitoring script every few minutes so the system information is always updated without manual work.â€

1ï¸âƒ£2ï¸âƒ£ What is the signature file, and why did you create it?
â€œThe signature file is a SHAâ€‘1 hash of my virtual machine disk. I created it to prove the VM has not been modified or tampered with, ensuring the integrity of the work I submitted.â€
